	<text>
		<body>
			<p><pb n="1" facs="EHRI-ET-DEGOB0086_01.jpg"/> The person in question has given us the following information: My <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-819" type="subject">father</term> was a grocer in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/724443/kosice.html">Kassa</placeName>. He had two houses, the third one had just started to be built
				then. We lived in a five-room flat with my parents and my two siblings; my father was definitely considered a rich man. He buried
				somewhere a lot of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-887" type="subject">money</term>, jewellery and
				receipts written by his Christian friends stating what and how much they had accepted from him for safekeeping. He, the poor man,
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">died</term> in <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2">Auschwitz</placeName>. I am the only one at home as yet and I do not
				know where he buried those valuables, so I do not know if I can ever get hold of them. My father was, on account of his decorations
				earned in the other war, exempt from <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-335" type="subject">Jewish
					law</term> together with his whole family. We did not have to wear the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-338" type="subject">yellow star</term> and when all the other Jews from
					<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/724443/kosice.html">Kassa</placeName> were sent to the <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/724443/kosice.html">ghetto</placeName>, we were told we did not have to go there. Yet, this was the
				time when my father tried to find a safe place for his valuables. Although, some days later a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1125" type="subject">gendarme</term> appeared and said that we had to go.
				After half an hour another one came and said we could stay. It went on like that for days, we lived in continuous anxiety; finally one
				day they <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-552" type="subject">took us to the ghetto</term> nevertheless.
				We had to get ready within an hour, and we could take with us what we wanted. I could have escaped but my parents insisted on our
				staying together. If they had suspected that our being together would last for such a short time, they might have let me <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-204" type="subject">escape</term>. They crammed the Jews in the brickyard
				of <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/724443/kosice.html">Kassa</placeName>, plenty of people in a very small place. We stayed
				there for four weeks. We lived mostly on what we had brought with us. Chief inspector Dr <persName ref="#ehri_et_csatari"
					>Csatári</persName> was continuously beating <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1207" type="subject"
					>people</term> with a dog whip. When it came to his mind, he went in the block and he <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-564" type="subject">hit</term> whomever he found there with the dog whip.
				On one occasion he ordered through a microphone every young <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-819"
					type="subject">girl</term> to come out. He took them out and forced them to dig out thick wooden stakes from the ground with their
				hands. Even the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216" type="subject">SS soldiers</term> were scandalized
				by this; they said that for them, such things are done with spades. Many <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1207" type="subject">people</term><term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-204" type="subject">escaped</term> from the brickyard. We were told that
				we would be taken to do agricultural <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term> but
				we would stay in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/719819/hungary.html">Hungary.</placeName>
				<pb n="2" facs="EHRI-ET-DEGOB0086_02.jpg"/> We would have liked to believe this, but we found it suspicious that <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216" type="subject">German soldiers</term> were there with us. One Sunday
				morning, they woke us up at 4 o'clock in the morning. <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1119"
					type="subject">Policemen</term> occupied the brickyard. We all had to gather at a large place and stand there in the blazing sun
				till 3 o'clock in the afternoon. They did not let us <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject"
					>eat</term> or go for water. A friend of mine <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-204" type="subject"
					>escaped</term> even from there. We were allowed to take a pillow and a duvet with us in the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject">cattle car</term>. 72 <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1207" type="subject">people</term> were in our <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject">cattle car</term> together with plenty of bedclothes
				and packages of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">food</term>. It was terribly hot in
				the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject">cattle car</term> and we were horribly thirsty.
				After a three-day journey we arrived in <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2">Auschwitz</placeName> on
					<date>21st May</date>. We had to jump out of the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject"
					>cattle cars</term> and we were told to leave our baggage there, they would be sent after us. They <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-411" type="subject">lined us up</term> and by the time I became aware of
				what was happening I had been in a group with one of my younger brothers but without my father. We who were able to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term> were taken to the bath; they stripped us
				naked and bathed us, then they took us to block No. 13. 5 <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-483"
					type="subject">people</term> had to find space on one berth. We made a lot of noise and then the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1438" type="subject">overseer</term> came in and struck us with a
				truncheon. That was the first beating. We lined up twice a day for <q><term
						ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-487" type="subject">Appell</term></q> and if somebody was not standing
				as upright as a ramrod, they struck him. Those who went out to the toilet were also <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-562" type="subject">beaten up</term>. Three days later we were taken to
					<placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-433">Wolfsberg</placeName>. We were put in <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">tents</term> made of cardboard, 3 metres in diameter,
				20 <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1207" type="subject">people</term> in each. We did a very hard <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term> there, first at road construction, then
				chiselled concrete in a tunnel. Our provisions consisted of 1/3 of a loaf of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">bread</term>, some black <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">coffee</term> in the morning and some <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">soup</term> without any content. We <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-569" type="subject">starved</term> terribly and became very weak. If they
				saw somebody getting hold of a raw <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">potato</term>, he
				received 25 strikes on his soles and they took the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject"
					>potato</term> away. One of their favourite punishments was that when we came back from <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term> and were tired, they made us do
				somersaults, or we had to be crouching or jumping for a quarter of an hour. They called it doing sports. After 12 hours of hard <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term> and being provisioned like that it was
				difficult to survive. 10-12 <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1207" type="subject">people</term><term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">died</term> every day. My leg developed a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-791" type="subject">tumour</term> and I had already been very weak then,
				so I was taken to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-491" type="subject">hospital</term>. I spent four
				months in <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-491" type="subject">hospital</term> and my leg was operated on
				but I could not regain my strength after that. It happened sometimes that the leader of the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-491" type="subject">hospital</term> did not give the patients <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">food</term> for a day. I was discharged from <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-491" type="subject">hospital</term> on <date>15th January</date> and they
				took me to <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-510">Wüstegiesdorf</placeName>. 800 <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1207" type="subject">people</term> lived there in a big <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">building</term>. I was very glad, because that <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496" type="subject">camp</term> was clean and washing in hot water was a
				daily obligation. The provisions were better in the sense that we could go to the city and there we could acquire some <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">food</term>. I was a gatekeeper and for this I
				received double <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">rations</term>. Much to my delight I
				met one of my uncles there, who worked at the kitchen and always gave me a little <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">food</term>. When the <orgName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-004583">Russians</orgName> were approaching, two of our comrades <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-204" type="subject">escaped</term>. We were packed up and we <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-517" type="subject">marched</term> 70 kilometres within 2 days in terrible
				cold. We arrived in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3077505/chvalec.html">Qualisch</placeName> on a Monday, but we were given
				something to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">eat</term> only on Friday. We suffered
				terribly from <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-569" type="subject">hunger</term>. What the peasants threw
				away, like rotten <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">potatoes</term> or <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">turnips</term>, we picked up from the rubbish pile and
				ate them. We already looked so bad that we did not even like to look at each other. Finally they put us in open freight cars, 60 <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1207" type="subject">people</term> in each. We were travelling for six
				days; it was snowing and we were suffering terribly from cold too. 6 people <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">died</term> in my freight car during that journey.
				Many <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1207" type="subject">people</term> went mad. 800 <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1207" type="subject">people</term> started from <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3099146/gluszyca.html">Wüstegiesdorf</placeName> and 500 of us arrived in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/2904789/hildesheim.html">Hildesheim</placeName>. And from those only 400 were able to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term>. <pb n="3" facs="EHRI-ET-DEGOB0086_03.jpg"
				/> We had to rebuild a train station destroyed by <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1105" type="subject"
					>bombs</term>. It was very hard <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term> to
				carry rails and sleepers when we had already been almost unable to drag ourselves along. The provisions were getting worse and worse
				every day. We received 1/6 of a loaf of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">bread</term>
				and some <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">soup</term> once a day, but it often
				happened that the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">bread</term> was omitted. The
				following case made a terrible impression on me: a freight car containing <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">food</term> destroyed by a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1105" type="subject">bomb</term> was standing on the train station. Those
				who could tried to get some <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">food</term> from it. One
				of the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216" type="subject">Scharführers</term> saw when a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-819" type="subject">boy</term> of 14 hid a tin of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">food</term> under his jacket. He ordered the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-819" type="subject">boy</term> to sit down on the ground and pressed his
				gun to his temple. The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-819" type="subject">child</term> began to beg, so
				he removed the revolver from there but he put it back in a minute. This game repeated again and again and it was awful to hear the
				fear of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">death</term> in the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-819" type="subject">child’s</term> voice, he was practically howling and
				whimpering of fear. When the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216" type="subject">German soldier</term>
				became bored with this amusement, he grabbed both hands of the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-819"
					type="subject">child</term> and <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532" type="subject">shot him</term>
				in the head. There was another case when a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-650" type="subject"
					>prisoner</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-204" type="subject">escaped</term> from the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496" type="subject">camp</term> but he was caught. The whole <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496" type="subject">camp</term> had to appear at the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-541" type="subject">hanging</term> and the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-819" type="subject">boy</term>'s <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-819" type="subject">father</term> was placed in the first row, right next
				to the gallows; he had to watch his <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-819" type="subject"
					>son’s</term><term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">death</term> till the end. In
					<placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-42">Belsen</placeName> the whole <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496" type="subject">camp</term> got <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-493" type="subject">typhus.</term> We had to carry or pull the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-515" type="subject">corpses</term> in our arms to the place of collection.
				In <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-723">Hannover</placeName>, we <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">worked</term> all the time at night in a tunnel; they
				said they were building an underground airplane factory. They beat us awfully there. Hits were raining upon us practically every
				minute. <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1207" type="subject">People</term> were falling down like flies
				in the autumn. We received half a litre of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject"
					>soup</term> every other day. We were suffering from <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-569"
					type="subject">hunger</term>. It happened there that one wretch cut some flesh out of the thigh of a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">dead man</term> and he also took his lungs out. The
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">dead man’s</term> fellows saw that and they took
				the man to the back and they beat him until he collapsed full of blood. When he recovered consciousness, they began to beat him again
				until he <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">died</term>. I will never forget that
				horrible episode. An <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216" type="subject">SS man</term> shot <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">dead</term> a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1427" type="subject">physician</term> called <persName
					ref="#ehri_et_schonstein">Schönstein</persName>, because he had gone out to pick some <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">carrots</term>. When the English <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-573" type="subject">came in</term>, they only found skeletons in our <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496" type="subject">camp</term>. We belonged already to the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">dead</term>, rather than living people.</p>
